'''Ōmiyanome''' (大宮売) is a [[Shinto]] [[deity]]. In the {{ill|Engishiki Jinmyōchō|ja|延喜式神名帳|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Kogo Shūi|ja|古語拾遺|12=draft|12=draft}}, she is written as '''Ōmiyanome no Kami''' (大宮売神), while at {{ill|Fushimi Inari-taisha|ja|伏見稲荷大社|12=draft|12=draft}}, she is referred to as '''Ōmiyanome no Ōkami''' (大宮能売大神).<ref name=gosaijin>{{Cite web|language=ja|url=http://inari.jp/about/saijin/|author=伏見稲荷大社 |title=伏見稲荷大社とは -ご祭神|accessdate=2016-04-15}}</ref> She is a goddess who protects the peace of {{ill|palaces|ja|宮殿|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name=inariookami>稲田智宏「稲荷大神五柱とは何か」『稲荷大神』、戎光祥出版、2009th year 。</ref>
== Mythological Descriptions == Ōmiyanome is not mentioned in either the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|12=draft|12=draft}} or the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft|12=draft}}, but she appears in the {{ill|Kogo Shūi|ja|古語拾遺|12=draft|12=draft}} as a child of {{ill|Futodama|ja|太玉命|12=draft|12=draft}}. She is described as serving as an attendant to {{ill|Amaterasu Ōmikami|ja|天照大神|1=Amaterasu|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami|12=draft|12=draft}} when the latter moved from the {{ill|Ama-no-Iwato|ja|天岩戸|1=Amano-Iwato|lt=Heavenly Rock Cave|12=draft|12=draft}} to a new palace. According to the text, she acted as a {{ill|court lady|ja|内侍|1=Naishi (court lady)|12=draft|12=draft}} who facilitated harmony between the emperor and his subjects through beautiful and wise words.
In the {{ill|Ōtono Hōgai Norito|ja|大殿祭祝詞|12=draft|12=draft}} found in the {{ill|Engishiki|ja|延喜式|12=draft|12=draft}}, she is described as a deity who resides in the [[Imperial Palace]] and ensures that the {{ill|Imperial princes|1=Shinnō|ja|親王|12=draft|12=draft}} and court ministers serve faithfully without error.
== Explanation == Ōmiyanome is one of the eight deities venerated by the {{ill|Jingikan|ja|神祇官|1=Department of Divinities|blank=|12=draft|12=draft}} for the protection of the [[Emperor of Japan|emperor]].<ref name=inariookami/> She has been described as a personification of the palace or the deification of court ladies. Her role is to mediate and harmonize the relationship between the emperor and his subjects.<ref name=tobe>{{Cite book|author=戸部民夫|title=「日本の神様」がよくわかる本|publisher=PHP研究所|year=2004|isbn=978-4569661155|pages=271–272}}</ref>
As one of the {{ill|Three Deities of Inari|ja|稲荷三神|12=draft|12=draft}} enshrined at {{ill|Fushimi Inari-taisha|ja|伏見稲荷大社|12=draft|12=draft}}, she is worshiped as a subordinate deity to {{ill|Ukanomitama|ja|ウカノミタマ|12=draft|12=draft}}, the main deity of the upper shrine.<ref name=inariookami/> Some interpretations suggest that she is a deified {{ill|miko|ja|巫女|12=draft|12=draft}} who served the agricultural deity Ukanomitama.<ref name=tobe/> Because of her attributes, she was worshipped as the guardian deity of official markets in {{ill|Heian-kyō|ja|平安京|12=draft|12=draft}}, eventually becoming associated with prosperity in business.<ref name=inariookami/>
Additionally, the Edo-period {{ill|kokugaku|ja|国学|12=draft|12=draft}} scholar {{ill|Hirata Atsutane|ja|平田篤胤|12=draft|12=draft}} argued in his text "Miyabinokami no Dengi" that the deity {{ill|Miyabinokami|ja|宮比神|12=draft|12=draft}} of the {{ill|Inner Shrine of Ise|ja|皇大神宮|1=Kōtai Jingū|2=ja|3=皇大神宮|4=zh|5=皇大神宮|12=draft|12=draft}} is another name for either Ōmiyanome or {{ill|Ame-no-Uzume|ja|アメノウズメ|12=draft|12=draft}}. At shrines like {{ill|Yūtoku Inari Shrine|ja|祐徳稲荷神社|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Shiwa Inari Shrine|ja|志和稲荷神社|12=draft|12=draft}}, Ōmiyanome is identified with Ame-no-Uzume and revered as a deity of artistic skill.<ref>{{Cite web|language=ja|url=https://www.yutokusan.jp/about/|title=お祀りする神様|publisher=祐徳稲荷神社|accessdate=2016-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|language=ja|url=http://www.shiwa-oinarisan.jp/about/|title=志和稲荷神社について|publisher=志和稲荷神社|accessdate=2016-04-16}}</ref>
== Shrines Dedicated to Ōmiyanome == [[File:Omiya-inari-jinja (Kyoto, Kyoto).JPG|thumb|200px|right|Ōmiya Hime Inari Shrine ({{ill|Kyoto|ja|京都市|12=draft|12=draft}})]] [[File:Omiyame-jinja, haiden.jpg|thumb|200px|right|{{ill|Ōmiyanome Shrine|ja|大宮売神社|12=draft|12=draft}} (Kyōtango City)]] Ōmiya Hime Inari Shrine, located near the former site of the {{ill|Jingikan|ja|神祇官|1=Department of Divinities|blank=|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Kyoto|ja|京都市|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Ōmiyanome Shrine|ja|大宮売神社|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Kyōtango|ja|京丹後市|12=draft|12=draft}}, the only {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|12=draft|12=draft}} bearing the name "Ōmiyanome," venerate her as the primary deity. Additionally, she is worshiped at {{ill|Fushimi Inari-taisha|ja|伏見稲荷大社|12=draft|12=draft}} and other {{ill|Inari Shrines|ja|稲荷神社|12=draft|12=draft}} across Japan as a subordinate deity of Ukanomitama.
